ht to navigate between tradition and modernity, between Jewish history and the German present, and between the fading walls of the ghetto and the promise of a new identity as members of a German bourgeoisie. This study examines the ways in which popular fiction assumed an unprecedented role in shaping Jewish identity during this period. It locates in nineteenth-century Germany a defining moment of the modern Jewish experience and the beginnings of a tradition of Jewish belles lettres that is in many ways still with us today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aGerman fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aGerman literaturexJewish authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aGroup identity in literature. 0aJewish fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aJews in literature. 0aJewszGermanyxIntellectual lifey19th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804774239zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804774239423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804774239.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles